WEBVTT

00:00:10.473 --> 00:00:11.890
NANCY KANWISHER:
OK, so we are now

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:15.160
going to do the third part
in our sort of trilogy

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:17.390
of uniquely human functions.

00:00:17.390 --> 00:00:19.510
So starting a few
weeks ago, we moved

00:00:19.510 --> 00:00:21.580
from things that are
shared with animals,

00:00:21.580 --> 00:00:25.630
like navigation and basic
visual perception-- very similar

00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:28.660
between humans and monkeys.

00:00:28.660 --> 00:00:31.960
And other number--
all of these things

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:35.140
that are shared with animals,
to talk about functions

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:36.460
that are uniquely human.

00:00:36.460 --> 00:00:38.750
And that includes
music and language.

00:00:38.750 --> 00:00:41.170
And today, we're going to talk
about the coolest and most

00:00:41.170 --> 00:00:43.900
quintessentially
human mental function

00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:48.100
and that is thinking about
each other's thoughts.

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:53.500
So to get started thinking
about this, let me remind you

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:55.720
guys of what should
be pretty obvious--

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.630
that we human beings
are profoundly

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:01.450
social in many, many
different respects.

00:01:01.450 --> 00:01:03.880
So if you think about--

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:05.620
if you recount what
happened in your day

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.020
to someone else, pretty much
all of the elements of what

00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:12.040
you're recounting our
interactions with other people.

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:13.580
These are the things
we care about.

00:01:13.580 --> 00:01:17.320
These are the basic
structure of our lives.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:21.430
Other people are the source
of our greatest happiness

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:22.480
for most of us.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:24.892
If you ask people at the end
of life what matters most,

00:01:24.892 --> 00:01:26.350
they'll say I
shouldn't have wasted

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:27.760
all that time working so hard.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.320
And my job didn't matter.

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:31.990
And I didn't realize, actually,
it's just other people are

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:35.290
the only thing that matter.

00:01:35.290 --> 00:01:37.450
Interactions with other
people, or lack thereof,

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:41.290
are also the source of
one of the deepest kinds

00:01:41.290 --> 00:01:43.760
of human suffering
for many of us,

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:48.820
whether it's an everyday thing
like a breakup with a lover,

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:53.110
or a loss of a loved
one, or a family member--

00:01:53.110 --> 00:01:56.390
and also depriving people
of social interactions.

00:01:56.390 --> 00:02:01.390
This is, like, society's kind
of strongest form of punishment,

00:02:01.390 --> 00:02:04.960
is solitary confinement.

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:07.090
Interactions with other people--

00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:08.889
our failure to
understand them is

00:02:08.889 --> 00:02:10.960
devastating in the
case of autism,

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:13.270
where people struggle
to understand what

00:02:13.270 --> 00:02:16.790
other people are all about.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:21.910
And in terms of our amazing
abilities as human beings,

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:25.180
most of what we know we
learn from other people.

00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:27.640
Sometimes, we figure
stuff out on our own.

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:30.450
But if you take an inventory
of all the stuff you know,

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:32.890
you read about it or
somebody told it to you.

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:36.310
You learned it
from other people.

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:40.210
And consequently, some of the
greatest feats of humanity,

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:43.270
from arts to science
to everything else,

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:46.990
are products of people
working together.

00:02:46.990 --> 00:02:51.430
OK, further, many people
have hypothesized that social

00:02:51.430 --> 00:02:54.190
cognition, or ability to
understand and deal with--

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:55.780
interact with other people--

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:58.660
is one of the strongest
drivers of the evolution

00:02:58.660 --> 00:02:59.840
of the human brain.

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:01.870
So many have argued
that the hardest

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:03.580
problem we solve
on a daily basis

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:05.480
is understanding other people.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:07.520
And it's also a very
important problem.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:10.495
And so that's a powerful
natural selection force,

00:03:10.495 --> 00:03:11.620
understanding other people.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:14.410
And that has shaped the
structure of the human brain.

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:16.930
Not everybody agrees with
that kind of extreme view,

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:19.000
that it's the primary
driver, but it's

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.170
an interesting hypothesis.

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:23.530
And it surely played some role.

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:27.310
Social cognition also is
just a very large percent

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:28.720
of human cognition.

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:32.530
And it's a large in terms
of minutes of every day.

00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:35.002
If you tally up different
forms of social cognition,

00:03:35.002 --> 00:03:36.460
this is one we're
doing right now--

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:39.400
and we're about to engage in
an hour and 20 minutes of it

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:40.025
right here.

00:03:40.025 --> 00:03:41.650
And probably, when
you leave this room,

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:43.820
you'll engage in other
kinds of social cognition.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:47.960
So it's just a large percent
what we do all day every day,

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:51.520
and it's also a large percent
of what the cortex does.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.750
So roughly that
stuff and other bits

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:59.950
are engaged in different
aspects of social cognition.

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:03.940
OK, so what exactly
