00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:05.930
OK, all right, so--
but focusing more

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:08.460
on the cognitive abilities.

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:12.350
What you need to do to figure
out another agent's actions

00:08:12.350 --> 00:08:15.990
is to figure out what
that agent is doing.

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:18.020
And that's externally
observable.

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:18.830
You can watch.

00:08:18.830 --> 00:08:21.530
You can use your perceptual
system, construed broadly,

00:08:21.530 --> 00:08:23.540
to figure out what
is this person doing

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:26.150
in some general sense.

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:28.910
And that's important, and
subtle, and multifaceted,

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:30.563
but it's nowhere near enough.

00:08:30.563 --> 00:08:31.980
Really, what you
want to know is--

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:34.340
why are they doing that thing?

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:37.429
OK, and that's not
directly observable.

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:40.820
You can't see the why
of a person's actions.

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:42.320
You have to infer it.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:44.840
In fact, to infer it,
you have to infer a bunch

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:47.030
of hidden mental states.

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:50.330
And those things are much
more abstract than just, I'm

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:51.877
picking up the phone.

00:08:51.877 --> 00:08:53.210
You know, that's just an action.

00:08:53.210 --> 00:08:54.460
You can see it.

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.960
But if you try to think about
why am I picking up the phone,

00:08:56.960 --> 00:08:59.970
now we're in a whole
different ballpark.

00:08:59.970 --> 00:09:02.390
And so what you
need to figure out,

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:05.630
to figure out the agent's
hidden mental states--

00:09:05.630 --> 00:09:09.500
you need to figure out what
can that agent see or hear.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:11.450
OK, and here, it's
really important

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:13.190
to not lose a level here.

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:16.100
We're not talking
about what we can see.

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:20.450
In understanding
another agent, we

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:22.700
need to understand
what that agent can

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:24.800
see about someone else.

00:09:24.800 --> 00:09:26.990
OK, so we're getting
kind of meta here--

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:28.070
multiple levels.

00:09:28.070 --> 00:09:33.770
OK, we also need to understand
the other agent's desires

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:39.290
and goals of what they want,
or what they're intending, OK.

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:42.950
So how might we figure
these things out?

00:09:42.950 --> 00:09:46.195
Sometimes, there are simple
cues that might suffice.

00:09:46.195 --> 00:09:48.320
So you might make an
inference like, if a person is

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.470
reaching for an object,
they want that object.

00:09:51.470 --> 00:09:54.590
OK, so there, the
externally observable thing

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:56.420
might give you a
pretty direct inference

00:09:56.420 --> 00:10:01.380
about the internal hidden
state of what the agent wants.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:03.980
OK, but a lot of times,
that's not going to work.

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:08.100
Right, that's going to work
in some cases, but only a few.

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:11.550
And further, the
percepts and the goals

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:14.280
that we've mentioned
here aren't enough.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:18.330
OK, they'll work in some
cases, but humans do much more

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:19.630
than that.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:21.690
So let's consider this case.

00:10:21.690 --> 00:10:27.180
Here's an agent who's
doing some action,

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:29.410
and we can observe
their body motions.

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:31.500
And what we want
to understand is

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:33.810
how this other
agent watching them

00:10:33.810 --> 00:10:36.540
is going to infer
things about this guy.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:38.490
OK, so we're
interested in what's

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:42.600
going on in the mind of this
guy, as they watch that guy.

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:45.840
OK, now let's consider
the case that this guy is

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.520
trying to understand--

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:48.600
this is Romeo here.

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:52.040
Why did Romeo reach
for the bottle?

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:57.640
OK, well to understand why
Romeo reached for the bottle,

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:01.740
you need to perceive and
infer a whole bunch of things.

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:05.880
You need to see the hand
reaching for the bottle

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:10.110
to know what happened, but
then to really understand

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:13.050
the case of Romeo,
you need to understand

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:16.080
that his intention is to drink
the liquid in the bottle.

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:17.760
That's why he reached for it.

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:20.340
OK, you can't see the
intention to drink the liquid.

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:22.560
You can only see the reaching.

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:24.060
Then, you further
need to understand

00:11:24.060 --> 00:11:28.192
why is he intending
to drink the liquid.

00:11:28.192 --> 00:11:30.150
Well, because he believes
the liquid is poison.

00:11:34.060 --> 00:11:37.810
I don't know why my pop ups are
all messing up here-- whatever.

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:42.680
He believes that Juliet is
dead, and he wants to die.

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:47.060
OK, so all of that
is part of what

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:51.710
is entailed in understanding why
Romeo reached for the bottle.

00:11:51.710 --> 00:11:57.140
OK, and crucially the stuff
in red, these things are--

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:01.410
the beliefs and desires are
not directly observable.

00:12:01.410 --> 00:12:05.670
They're highly abstract.

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:06.720
And they're crucial.

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:09.910
They are the best way to
explain and predict behavior.

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:11.850
So when we need to
understand other people

00:12:11.850 --> 00:12:13.770
and what they're
doing and why, we're

00:12:13.770 --> 00:12:17.370
in this abstract space
of beliefs and desires.

00:12:17.370 --> 00:12:18.880
We can't see them directly.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:19.780
We have to observe.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:22.170
We have to infer
them indirectly.

00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:23.913
And they're essential,
because that's

00:12:23.913 --> 00:12:25.830
what we need to do to
understand other people.

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:33.680
All right, so we talked before
about perceiving an agent--

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:37.100
I'm sorry, about inferring
what an agent can perceive,

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:39.890
and inferring the agent's
desires and goals.

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:41.990
But as I just
pointed out, we also

00:12:41.990 --> 00:12:46.130
need to know the agent's
beliefs-- what they think.

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:48.980
So all of this stuff
in here, inferring

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:51.560
the hidden mental
states of agents

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:54.590
is what we mean by mentalizing,
inferring other people's

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:55.880
mental states.

00:12:55.880 --> 00:12:58.220
OK, in the cases we're
talking about here,

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:00.770
we're inferring the
percepts of another agent,

00:13:00.770 --> 00:13:03.440
inferring the desires
of another agent,

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:05.780
and inferring the beliefs
of another agent--

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:08.450
OK, all this abstract stuff.

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:12.800
OK, no computer system can
do this, not even close.

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:13.970
See, we can still say that.

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:16.095
We can't say that about
object recognition anymore,

00:13:16.095 --> 00:13:18.440
but we have this
little precious reserve

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:20.690
where we can still say that.

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:24.080
No animal can do these things,
except in very restricted

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:24.810
cases.

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:27.740
So there's an active,
ongoing research program

00:13:27.740 --> 00:13:31.310
and a bunch of labs testing
chimps in subtle tasks

00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:33.290
to try to figure out when
they can infer things

00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:36.210
about the mind of another
chimp or a person.

00:13:36.210 --> 00:13:38.150
And there are a few
restricted cases

00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:39.620
where they can make
some inferences

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:41.840
about the mental
contents of other agents,

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:44.720
but the current dominant view
is that those inferences are

00:13:44.720 --> 00:13:48.800
very restricted to very
particular situations,

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:51.470
usually involving
competition over food.

00:13:51.470 --> 00:13:55.640
And they don't
generalize in any way.

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:59.480
OK, so in this whole
enterprise, specific cues

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:02.240
like making an
inference that reaching

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:05.600
for x means wanting x
will help in some cases,

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:07.820
but will only get us so far.

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:12.200
OK, we do much more than
that, and the question is how.

00:14:12.200 --> 00:14:15.590
All right, so
inferring mental states

00:14:15.590 --> 00:14:17.780
to understand other
people involves

00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:21.480
inferring their percepts, their
beliefs, and their desires.

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:25.170
OK, so how do we do this?

00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:28.400
Well, a first question
that we ask in this class,

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:30.260
and it's kind of a
sensible thing to do,

00:14:30.260 --> 00:14:33.260
is we were trying to understand
this whole space of how people

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:36.350
think about another agent's
percepts, beliefs, and desires.

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:38.660
We might just think,
OK, maybe that's just

00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:40.340
part of generic cognition.

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:43.327
Who says that's a separate
domain of cognition

00:14:43.327 --> 00:14:44.660
that we should study separately?

00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:47.450
Maybe we should just
study thinking in general.

00:14:47.450 --> 00:14:49.700
Thinking about objects,
thinking about physics,

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:52.760
thinking about people, maybe
it's all the same thing.

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:56.300
OK, so let's start
by considering,

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:59.850
is it really a separate thing
from the rest of cognition?

00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:03.090
OK, well, there's a
classic behavioral paradigm

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:06.362
in this field that's provided
some evidence in this.

00:15:06.362 --> 00:15:08.320
You may have heard about
this in other classes,

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:09.360
but we'll talk about
it, because it's

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:11.130
so kind of fundamental
to all of the work

00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:13.860
on thinking about other
people's thoughts.

00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:16.410
And that is called the
false belief paradigm.

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:18.990
It's really a way
of testing beliefs.

00:15:18.990 --> 00:15:21.480
And the reason you test
false beliefs rather than

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:27.180
true beliefs is if you ask about
another agent's true beliefs,

00:15:27.180 --> 00:15:29.610
then your prediction about
what they're going to do next

00:15:29.610 --> 00:15:32.590
is confounded with what
is true in the world.

00:15:32.590 --> 00:15:34.500
And if you want to
really tap into what's

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:38.700
going on in their mind,
as opposed to what

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:40.200
would be true in
the world, you have

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:42.510
to use a false belief
to pull those apart.

00:15:42.510 --> 00:15:45.180
OK, so the classic
way this is done,

00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:48.805
the Sally-Anne task
goes like this.

00:15:48.805 --> 00:15:50.430
There are many variants
of it, but this

00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:52.950
is the classic,
original version that

00:15:52.950 --> 00:15:55.530
appears in hundreds of papers.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:16:00.120
So here's Sally and Anne,
and Sally puts her ball

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:01.620
in the basket.

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:04.320
OK, you show this
to little kids--

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:06.600
or animals, too,
versions of it--

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:08.130
we're doing the
little kid version.

00:16:08.130 --> 00:16:09.242
You say OK, here's Sally.

00:16:09.242 --> 00:16:10.575
She puts her ball in the basket.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:15.330
I don't know why my pop
ups are screwing up.

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:17.610
Anyway, then Anne comes along.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.560
Sally leaves the
room, Anne comes in,

00:16:19.560 --> 00:16:23.280
and moves Sally's ball
from the basket to the box,

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:25.890
and closes the top of the box.

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:29.070
Then the question is,
when Sally comes back,

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:31.218
where will she
look for her ball?

00:16:31.218 --> 00:16:32.760
OK, where will she
look for her ball?

00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:38.550
In the basket, right.

00:16:38.550 --> 00:16:42.480
OK, if you do this very simple
question for three-year-olds,

00:16:42.480 --> 00:16:45.150
they'll say in the box.

00:16:45.150 --> 00:16:49.360
If you do it on five-year-olds,
they'll say in the basket.

00:16:49.360 --> 00:16:51.690
OK, adults say in the basket--

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:53.417
you have to think
for a second, right.

00:16:53.417 --> 00:16:55.500
If you just kind of blurt
out the first thing that

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.583
comes to mind, you'll
behave like a three-year-old

00:16:57.583 --> 00:16:58.620
and say in the box.

00:16:58.620 --> 00:17:02.048
But if you think for half
a second, you realize, duh,

00:17:02.048 --> 00:17:03.840
she doesn't know what
got moved to the box.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:05.940
She'll look where
she thinks it is--

00:17:05.940 --> 00:17:06.930
in the basket.

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:09.060
OK, everybody with
the program here?

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:11.770
OK so that's a very,
very simple task.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:14.849
It's the basic false
belief paradigm.

00:17:14.849 --> 00:17:16.230
And to make it
more vivid, I have

00:17:16.230 --> 00:17:18.839
to show you the video
of Rebecca Saxe giving

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:21.089
this task to a bunch of
kids and talking about it.

00:17:21.089 --> 00:17:23.339
It's a delightful
video, and I'll

00:17:23.339 --> 00:17:27.900
give you a really vivid sense of
how smart a three-year-old is,

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:29.970
and how much they
understand, and yet

00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:33.778
how fundamentally and
totally they fail this task--

00:17:33.778 --> 00:17:34.695
versions of this task.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:38.433
Come on, here we go.

00:17:38.433 --> 00:17:39.100
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

