00:20:05.350 --> 00:20:07.183
because he doesn't want
to, because now it's

00:20:07.183 --> 00:20:08.090
dirty on the ground.

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:10.630
So that's why he's taking
the other sandwich.

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:14.170
Now, of course, development
doesn't end at 5.

00:20:14.170 --> 00:20:16.870
And we can see the
continuation of this process

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:19.000
of learning to think about
other people's thoughts

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.670
by upping the ante and
asking children now

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:24.670
not for an action prediction,
but for a moral judgment.

00:20:24.670 --> 00:20:27.460
So first, I'm going to show
you the three-year-old again.

00:20:27.460 --> 00:20:30.535
Was Ivan being mean and naughty
for taking Joshua's sandwich?

00:20:30.535 --> 00:20:31.280
- Yeah.

00:20:31.280 --> 00:20:31.780
- Yeah.

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:34.570
- Should Ivan get in trouble
for taking Joshua's sandwich?

00:20:34.570 --> 00:20:35.980
- Yeah.

00:20:35.980 --> 00:20:38.590
- So it's maybe not surprising--
he thinks it was mean of Ivan

00:20:38.590 --> 00:20:41.860
to take Joshua's sandwich,
since he thinks Ivan only took

00:20:41.860 --> 00:20:44.110
Joshua's sandwich to avoid
having to eat his own dirty

00:20:44.110 --> 00:20:44.980
sandwich.

00:20:44.980 --> 00:20:47.110
But now, I'm going to show
you the five-year-old.

00:20:47.110 --> 00:20:48.880
Remember, the
five-year-old completely

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:51.460
understood why Ivan
took Joshua's sandwich.

00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:53.080
- Was Ivan being
mean and naughty

00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:56.170
for taking Joshua's sandwich?

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:56.740
- Yeah.

00:20:56.740 --> 00:21:00.070
- And so it's not until age
7 that we get what looks more

00:21:00.070 --> 00:21:02.050
like an adult response.

00:21:02.050 --> 00:21:05.120
Should Ivan get in trouble
for taking Joshua's sandwich?

00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:07.150
- No, because the wind
should get in trouble.

00:21:07.150 --> 00:21:08.026
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:08.902 --> 00:21:12.442
- The wind should get in trouble
for switching his sandwiches.

00:21:12.442 --> 00:21:13.765
[END PLAYBACK]

00:21:14.265 --> 00:21:15.640
NANCY KANWISHER:
OK, so everybody

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:17.980
got the idea of the
false belief tasks--

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:20.290
passed in the four
and five-year-olds,

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:21.760
not in the three-year-old.

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:25.060
And the three-year-old not only
fails to get the answer right,

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:26.860
but when asked why
it happened, he

00:21:26.860 --> 00:21:28.678
comes up with a totally
different account.

00:21:28.678 --> 00:21:30.970
OK, and you can see that
three-year-old is not a dummy.

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:33.940
Three-year-olds are smart and
can do all kinds of things,

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:37.060
but they don't get
this particular thing.

00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:41.855
OK, all right, what
about kids with autism?

00:21:44.590 --> 00:21:49.560
Well, kids with autism either
failed this task altogether,

00:21:49.560 --> 00:21:53.130
or they pass it much later
than neurotypical kids.

00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:57.390
OK, but now we've got
to figure out why.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:22:01.380
Why would a relatively high
functioning kid with autism--

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:04.070
say, a 7-year-old
who's got language,

00:22:04.070 --> 00:22:05.820
and who seems to
understand the question--

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:07.140
why would they fail this task?

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:09.240
Why would anybody
fail this task?

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.230
There's a couple of
things going on here.

00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:14.010
The essential element of
the false belief tasks

00:22:14.010 --> 00:22:17.160
that we're interested in is that
it requires you to attribute

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:18.720
thoughts to another agent.

00:22:18.720 --> 00:22:21.690
Right, that's what this
task was made to tap.

00:22:21.690 --> 00:22:24.918
But you might fail it not
just for failing to attribute

00:22:24.918 --> 00:22:25.710
thoughts correctly.

00:22:25.710 --> 00:22:27.840
You might fail it
for other reasons.

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:31.530
You might fail it because
this task involves

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:34.620
this weird situation where
there's the other agent's

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:38.010
belief, and there's a reality,
and they're different.

00:22:38.010 --> 00:22:39.670
And that's kind of confusing.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:42.690
It's like representing x
and not x at the same time.

00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:46.350
Maybe that's just a particularly
generically hard cognitive

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:49.410
thing to do, OK.

00:22:49.410 --> 00:22:52.410
And the third possibility
is that the true state

00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.380
of the world is so
salient and dominant,

00:22:55.380 --> 00:22:58.920
it may be hard to just inhibit
that true reality in order

00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:02.130
to infer the belief--

00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:04.635
a belief is a kind of less
visible, salient thing

00:23:04.635 --> 00:23:06.010
than the true
state of the world.

00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:09.900
And so maybe just having an
inability to inhibit dominant,

00:23:09.900 --> 00:23:13.230
salient representations would
interfere with your ability

00:23:13.230 --> 00:23:14.530
to do this task.

00:23:14.530 --> 00:23:17.850
So people with autism, or,
in fact, three-year-olds,

00:23:17.850 --> 00:23:19.870
might fail for any
of these reasons.

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:23.130
So how are we going to figure
out whether people with autism

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:27.510
are actually failing this task
because of their difficulty

00:23:27.510 --> 00:23:30.462
in attributing thoughts?

00:23:30.462 --> 00:23:31.920
Well, the way to
figure that out is

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:35.850
to come up with a really,
really clever control task.

00:23:35.850 --> 00:23:38.260
This task was invented
by Debbie Zaitchik

00:23:38.260 --> 00:23:39.510
when I was in graduate school.

00:23:39.510 --> 00:23:41.408
She was my office mate
in graduate school,

00:23:41.408 --> 00:23:42.700
and she came up with this task.

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:44.280
And I said, that is
really brilliant.

00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:47.850
So we want to figure out
whether it's the belief, per se,

00:23:47.850 --> 00:23:50.700
that's the difficulty
in attributing

00:23:50.700 --> 00:23:52.860
the thought or the belief
to another agent that's

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:54.400
the crux of the problem.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:57.120
So in Zaitchik's
false photo task,

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:00.120
the idea is it's a
logically isomorphic task,

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:02.760
but it's about a physical
representation, not

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:04.320
a mental one.

00:24:04.320 --> 00:24:11.610
So what you do is you show Sally
putting her ball in the basket.

00:24:11.610 --> 00:24:16.850
And then you have what was then,
like, widely known to kids,

00:24:16.850 --> 00:24:20.070
a Polaroid photograph--
a camera come along.

00:24:20.070 --> 00:24:22.140
We didn't have cell
phones back then,

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:25.410
so it was a Polaroid camera--
takes a picture of Sally

00:24:25.410 --> 00:24:28.440
putting her ball in
the basket, and then

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:32.130
Anne moves the ball from
the basket to the box.

00:24:32.130 --> 00:24:40.890
And then you ask the kid, where
will Sally look for her ball--

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:43.260
I'm sorry, where is--

00:24:43.260 --> 00:24:45.270
sorry, then you
ask the kid, where

00:24:45.270 --> 00:24:46.890
is the ball in the photograph?

00:24:47.740 --> 00:24:51.500
OK, sorry, I screwed it up.

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:52.670
Here's a belief version.

00:24:52.670 --> 00:24:56.030
The kid watches Sally and Anne.

00:24:56.030 --> 00:24:59.180
In this case, you do a
photograph version of it,

00:24:59.180 --> 00:25:01.730
so there's no--

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:03.920
you're not asking about
another person's beliefs.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:05.120
You're using a photograph.

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:08.780
And you're showing Sally
put the ball in the basket.

00:25:08.780 --> 00:25:12.590
You take a photograph of it,
Anne moves the ball to the box.

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:17.990
And then you ask in the
photograph, where's the ball?

00:25:17.990 --> 00:25:21.410
OK, you're not asking
about a mental belief,

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:24.290
you're asking about a
physical representation

00:25:24.290 --> 00:25:26.060
in the photograph.

00:25:26.060 --> 00:25:29.210
OK, so do you see how--
even though I bungled it

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:33.710
on the first time-- it's really
a logically isomorphic task.

00:25:33.710 --> 00:25:36.680
In both cases, you're asking
about a representation that

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:40.400
differs from reality, but
one's a mental representation.

00:25:40.400 --> 00:25:42.590
That's where the kids
with autism fail the task.

00:25:42.590 --> 00:25:44.930
This is the physical
representation.

00:25:44.930 --> 00:25:48.920
Kids with ASD fail the
false belief task, not

00:25:48.920 --> 00:25:51.410
the false photo task.

00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:53.390
And that rules out
these other accounts,

00:25:53.390 --> 00:25:56.270
because in both cases,
there's a representation that

00:25:56.270 --> 00:25:57.260
differs from reality.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:25:59.780
You have the x and not
x challenge-- right,

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:01.880
that's true of both of these.

00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:04.190
And in both cases,
the true state

00:26:04.190 --> 00:26:07.460
is kind of more dominant than
the representational state

00:26:07.460 --> 00:26:09.710
in the belief, or the photo.

00:26:09.710 --> 00:26:13.970
And yet, they have a problem
with the belief version,

00:26:13.970 --> 00:26:15.950
not with the photograph
version, suggesting

00:26:15.950 --> 00:26:18.493
that this is the correct
account of why they fail.

00:26:18.493 --> 00:26:19.160
That make sense?

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:20.720
Was there a question?

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:23.510
Yeah-- OK.

00:26:23.510 --> 00:26:25.730
So all of that is
consistent with the idea

00:26:25.730 --> 00:26:28.670
that attributing
thoughts to another agent

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:32.640
is a special, distinctive
thing that can be--

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:34.400
that's what I just said.

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:37.640
So we have evidence that
attributing thoughts is

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:39.530
a distinct domain of cognition.

00:26:39.530 --> 00:26:41.810
It's just not part of
your generic ability

00:26:41.810 --> 00:26:42.830
to think about anything.

00:26:42.830 --> 00:26:45.950
And we see that from the fact
that typical children have

00:26:45.950 --> 00:26:48.890
this very systematic
developmental time

00:26:48.890 --> 00:26:50.630
course, where they
get this at age five,

00:26:50.630 --> 00:26:52.370
they don't get it at age three.

00:26:52.370 --> 00:26:54.710
And we see it from
the selective loss

00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:58.730
of this ability in
kids with autism,

00:26:58.730 --> 00:27:01.850
that they get the false belief
task way later than they

00:27:01.850 --> 00:27:03.380
get the false photograph task.

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:04.550
Was there a question here?

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:07.970
AUDIENCE: So the kids are never
asked what does Anne perceive.

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:10.430
That question then comes
up in the FP task--

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:13.358
in the false photograph task?

00:27:13.358 --> 00:27:14.900
NANCY KANWISHER:
I'm sure people have

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:16.760
done versions of that
task, but tell me

00:27:16.760 --> 00:27:18.340
what you're getting at here.

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:20.780
AUDIENCE: I just want to know
whether-- to do an accurate

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:23.900
comparison, I would assume
that the final question remains

00:27:23.900 --> 00:27:24.630
the same.

00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:29.210
So I would ask the kid, what do
you think Anne perceives given

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:30.860
the change in the stimulus.

00:27:30.860 --> 00:27:35.030
And then the kid responds, given
the new material, as to what

00:27:35.030 --> 00:27:35.690
the answer--

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:37.040
NANCY KANWISHER: You're trying
to get a tighter control

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:38.237
to the false photo task.

00:27:38.237 --> 00:27:39.320
AUDIENCE: Very much, yeah.

00:27:39.320 --> 00:27:41.320
NANCY KANWISHER: Yeah,
instead of where will she

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:42.860
look for the ball-- yeah.

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:45.020
But it's not really
about what she perceives.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:47.750
It's about where she
thinks the ball is.

00:27:47.750 --> 00:27:48.380
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:50.840
NANCY KANWISHER: And so
the false belief tasks

00:27:50.840 --> 00:27:53.862
have been done every
which way, from where

00:27:53.862 --> 00:27:55.820
does Sally think the ball
is, to where will she

00:27:55.820 --> 00:27:56.570
look for the ball.

00:27:56.570 --> 00:27:58.800
And you get the same
answer in all of those.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:02.293
So I think that's closer to,
where is it in the-- where

00:28:02.293 --> 00:28:03.710
is it in the
photograph is really,

00:28:03.710 --> 00:28:05.480
where does she think it is?

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:07.143
That's the parallel.

00:28:07.143 --> 00:28:09.560
Yeah, because she's not still
perceiving it at that point.

00:28:12.020 --> 00:28:14.643
OK, so that's
behavioral evidence

00:28:14.643 --> 00:28:16.310
to suggest that there's
really something

00:28:16.310 --> 00:28:19.160
different about inferring
another person's thoughts

00:28:19.160 --> 00:28:21.890
and beliefs than there is
from the rest of cognition--

00:28:21.890 --> 00:28:23.930
the distinctive
developmental time

00:28:23.930 --> 00:28:27.380
course and this kind of
selective deficit in autism.

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:29.990
So what can we learn
from functional MRI?

00:28:29.990 --> 00:28:31.670
Is there a special
part of the brain

00:28:31.670 --> 00:28:34.610
for making these inferences
about other agents, thoughts,

00:28:34.610 --> 00:28:36.390
and beliefs.

00:28:36.390 --> 00:28:40.830
OK, so Rebecca and I did
this experiment 100 years ago

00:28:40.830 --> 00:28:42.570
where we scanned
people while they

00:28:42.570 --> 00:28:45.870
were doing simple verbal tasks.

00:28:45.870 --> 00:28:48.510
So we wrote false
belief stories,

00:28:48.510 --> 00:28:50.670
and sort of false
photo stories--

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:52.920
generalized-- and
we scanned people

00:28:52.920 --> 00:28:54.930
while they lay in the
scanner and just read

00:28:54.930 --> 00:28:57.510
these simple descriptions
and answered basic questions.

00:28:57.510 --> 00:28:59.040
So you can try this right now.

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:01.800
Here's a false belief story.

00:29:01.800 --> 00:29:05.130
You read-- Susie parked her
sports car in the driveway

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:06.420
in the middle of the night.

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:08.220
Nathan moved her
car into the garage

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:10.350
to make room for his minivan.

00:29:10.350 --> 00:29:12.750
Susie woke up early
in the morning.

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:15.750
Susie expects to see
in the driveway--

00:29:15.750 --> 00:29:17.890
a sports car or a minivan?

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:18.390
Yes.

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:22.270
Sports car, duh.

00:29:22.270 --> 00:29:23.350
Right, exactly.

00:29:23.350 --> 00:29:25.990
What she thinks is
there, not what is there.

00:29:25.990 --> 00:29:30.010
The control experiment that--
we wrote many, many of these--

00:29:30.010 --> 00:29:32.260
a volcano erupted on
this Caribbean island

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:33.220
three months ago.

00:29:33.220 --> 00:29:35.590
Barren lava rock is
all that remains.

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:41.180
Satellite photos show the island
as it was before the eruption.

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:44.940
In the photos, the island is
covered in rock or vegetation,

00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:45.440
right.

00:29:46.460 --> 00:29:51.980
OK, so here again, it's just
like Debbie Zaitchik's ASD

00:29:51.980 --> 00:29:52.700
control here.

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:55.940
It's-- you're asking about a
representation in the satellite

00:29:55.940 --> 00:29:58.440
photo that's no longer
true of reality.

00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:00.180
And you have to
distinguish the two.

00:30:00.180 --> 00:30:02.570
So we scan people just
doing these tasks.

00:30:02.570 --> 00:30:06.890
OK, and if you look in a
whole brain group analysis

00:30:06.890 --> 00:30:10.802
that I was much dissing before,
but that's a good first step,

00:30:10.802 --> 00:30:13.010
you see-- here's a slice
through the brain like this.

00:30:13.010 --> 00:30:14.750
You see a bunch
of hot spots that

00:30:14.750 --> 00:30:18.470
respond more when you do
these tasks than those tasks.

00:30:18.470 --> 00:30:23.270
OK, and there's a
bunch of these regions.

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:26.888
Deep down in the middle of
the prefrontal cortex here

00:30:26.888 --> 00:30:28.430
that you can see in
a slice like that

00:30:28.430 --> 00:30:33.110
here is a region called MPFC
for medial prefrontal cortex.

00:30:33.110 --> 00:30:34.800
It does all kinds of
interesting things,

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:37.250
and it will get mostly short
shrift in this lecture.

00:30:37.250 --> 00:30:38.990
It activates in this task--

00:30:38.990 --> 00:30:43.040
for reasons you'll see in a
minute, activates in this task.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:47.300
Oh god, pop ups have
a mind of their own.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:50.250
But here's another
region, the right TPJ--

00:30:50.250 --> 00:30:52.970
TPJ stands for
temporoparietal junction.

00:30:52.970 --> 00:30:55.560
So in me, if my temporal
lobe is going down here,

00:30:55.560 --> 00:30:57.560
my parietal lobe is here,
frontal lobe is there.

00:30:57.560 --> 00:31:00.590
Temporoparietal junction is
somewhere right around there.

00:31:00.590 --> 00:31:03.890
OK-- everybody oriented?

00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:08.000
And if we look at that region,
shown symbolically here, what

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:11.060
you see in the time
course of response

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:13.550
in that region doing
this task, is here's

00:31:13.550 --> 00:31:15.560
what happens in that region.

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:17.450
This is time here--
many seconds,

00:31:17.450 --> 00:31:19.410
as they read and
answer that task.

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:21.980
And here's what happens
when they read and answer

00:31:21.980 --> 00:31:25.070
the false photo task-- so false
belief task, false photo task.

00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:27.810
That just shows you the
same thing's activation.

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:30.540
You can see it evolve over time.

00:31:30.540 --> 00:31:36.350
OK, so what happens
in the MPFC region--

00:31:36.350 --> 00:31:40.558
oh god, why is
this not happening.

00:31:40.558 --> 00:31:41.350
Is that showing up?

00:31:41.350 --> 00:31:43.450
Oh, there it is, OK.

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:46.600
Right-- in the MPFC region,
you see a similar thing.

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:49.528
You get a response
below baseline here.

00:31:49.528 --> 00:31:51.070
We'll talk about
that-- what it means

00:31:51.070 --> 00:31:52.630
to have a response
below baseline

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:54.790
in some conditions
in the next lecture.

00:31:54.790 --> 00:31:56.530
It's actually not
all that mysterious.

00:31:56.530 --> 00:31:59.410
It just means that baseline,
remember, is usually

00:31:59.410 --> 00:32:02.947
lying in the scanner staring at
a dot-- going dum dee dum dee

00:32:02.947 --> 00:32:04.780
dum-- or whatever you
do when you're staring

00:32:04.780 --> 00:32:06.790
at a dot in the scanner.

00:32:06.790 --> 00:32:10.150
And the key point for
now is just that you also

00:32:10.150 --> 00:32:13.270
see a higher response to
the belief than photo case.

00:32:13.270 --> 00:32:16.915
OK, so what's going
on in these regions?

00:32:19.860 --> 00:32:21.990
This activation,
this higher response,

00:32:21.990 --> 00:32:23.820
to the belief than photo case--

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:26.430
even though I was touting what
a brilliant control condition

00:32:26.430 --> 00:32:28.770
the false photo task is--

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:32.860
but it's still open to a bunch
of different possibilities.

00:32:32.860 --> 00:32:37.710
OK, so those activations
could be just thinking

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:38.820
about a person.

00:32:38.820 --> 00:32:42.780
After all, our false belief
stories all involve people,

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:45.300
and our false photo
stories did not.

00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:47.370
So maybe this isn't
about beliefs per se,

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:49.860
it's just about thinking
about people in general--

00:32:49.860 --> 00:32:51.570
any aspect of people.

00:32:51.570 --> 00:32:58.350
OK, or it could be
any mental inference

00:32:58.350 --> 00:33:03.150
we make about the internal,
invisible states of a person.

00:33:03.150 --> 00:33:08.190
OK-- anything that might
be going on in their head.

00:33:08.190 --> 00:33:11.250
Or it might be, particularly,
attributing thoughts

00:33:11.250 --> 00:33:14.370
and desires to the person.

00:33:14.370 --> 00:33:18.510
OK, so how are we going
to unconfound these--

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:20.830
with a new experiment
and some new conditions.

00:33:20.830 --> 00:33:24.450
So here's a new condition
that refers just to a person,

00:33:24.450 --> 00:33:26.850
not about their internal
invisible states,

00:33:26.850 --> 00:33:29.040
or their thoughts or desires.

00:33:29.040 --> 00:33:31.380
Subjects just read
simple stories like--

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:36.142
I see what's happening.

00:33:36.142 --> 00:33:37.850
It's not showing--
it's showing something

00:33:37.850 --> 00:33:40.850
different on the screen from
what's on my slide here.

00:33:40.850 --> 00:33:41.940
I have no idea why.

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:44.750
But anyway, that's why I
keep wondering what's there

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:46.700
and what's not.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:49.510
OK, so in the external
case, in this condition,

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:51.260
you lie in the scanner
and you read stuff,

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:53.340
like, Andrew just
had a growth spurt,

00:33:53.340 --> 00:33:55.400
so he was gangly
and rather awkward.

00:33:55.400 --> 00:33:59.300
Like most teenagers, he had bad
skin and bad taste in clothes.

00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:02.180
He wore mostly baggy
jeans and flannel shirts.

00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:05.700
OK, so it's not riveting,
but it's not boring either.

00:34:05.700 --> 00:34:07.950
You read a bunch of these,
they're interesting enough.

00:34:07.950 --> 00:34:12.409
OK-- but no mental states
there, just outward appearance.

00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:15.590
OK the next condition
refers directly

00:34:15.590 --> 00:34:18.110
to the person's thoughts--

00:34:18.110 --> 00:34:20.360
Nicky knew that his sister's
flight from San Francisco

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:21.830
was delayed 10 hours.

00:34:21.830 --> 00:34:24.650
Only one flight was
delayed so much that night,

00:34:24.650 --> 00:34:28.699
so when he got to the airport,
he knew what flight was hers.

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:31.550
OK, not even that
interesting, but it's

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:34.580
talking about what he inferred,
what he knew-- beliefs.

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:38.670
OK, but there's
a third condition

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:41.190
that refers to an
internal state,

00:34:41.190 --> 00:34:42.450
but not a thought or a belief.

00:34:42.450 --> 00:34:45.181
It refers to a visceral state.

00:34:45.181 --> 00:34:47.639
Sheila skipped breakfast because
she was late for the train

00:34:47.639 --> 00:34:48.306
to her mother's.

00:34:48.306 --> 00:34:50.880
By the time she got off the
train, she was starving.

00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:54.870
Her stomach was rumbling and
she could smell food everywhere.

00:34:54.870 --> 00:34:56.489
OK, so this case is interesting.

00:34:56.489 --> 00:34:57.480
It's vivid.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:00.600
It refers to a mental
state, but not a thought.

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:03.390
It's a physical state, hunger.

00:35:03.390 --> 00:35:06.930
OK, I mean it's a
mental representation

00:35:06.930 --> 00:35:08.740
of a bodily sensation.

00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:10.650
OK, everybody get
the distinction

00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:14.520
between internal thoughts
and feelings, sensations?

00:35:14.520 --> 00:35:19.140
OK, so this contrast
is consistent with any

00:35:19.140 --> 00:35:20.370
of these hypotheses.

00:35:20.370 --> 00:35:22.890
And we're going to test those
hypotheses with these three

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:24.300
conditions.

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:29.605
OK, so here are the
three hypotheses

00:35:29.605 --> 00:35:31.980
we just described here, and
here are the three conditions

00:35:31.980 --> 00:35:33.000
I just gave.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:34.890
And I want you guys
to tell me what

00:35:34.890 --> 00:35:38.880
we're going to predict that
we will see in the right TPJ

00:35:38.880 --> 00:35:40.805
according to each hypothesis--

00:35:40.805 --> 00:35:42.180
namely, which of
these conditions

00:35:42.180 --> 00:35:43.890
will produce a high
response, and which

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.410
will produce a low response.

00:35:46.410 --> 00:35:49.680
OK, so let's start
with this case--

00:35:49.680 --> 00:35:52.350
on the hypothesis
that the right TPJ

00:35:52.350 --> 00:35:55.680
responds whenever you're
reading about a person,

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:56.993
what are we going to find?

00:35:56.993 --> 00:35:58.410
Which of these
conditions is going

00:35:58.410 --> 00:35:59.535
to produce a high response?

00:36:01.554 --> 00:36:02.970
AUDIENCE: All of them?

00:36:02.970 --> 00:36:05.010
NANCY KANWISHER: All of
them, yeah, absolutely.

00:36:05.010 --> 00:36:07.110
So that's the prediction
here-- all of them.

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:12.420
OK, what about if it's
interested in internal bodily

00:36:12.420 --> 00:36:17.355
sensations, or actually, in
any internal mental states?

00:36:20.550 --> 00:36:22.800
The last two, absolutely--
both the visceral case

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:23.790
and the thoughts case.

00:36:23.790 --> 00:36:25.500
Sorry-- that cell and that cell.

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:28.620
OK, and what about
if it's specifically

00:36:28.620 --> 00:36:32.400
about attributing
thoughts to another agent.

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:34.050
Just the last one, right--

00:36:34.050 --> 00:36:35.430
OK, very good.

00:36:35.430 --> 00:36:37.420
So what do we see?

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:39.780
So first of all, here's
just a localizer task.

00:36:39.780 --> 00:36:42.047
Always nice to look at your
localizer and make sure

00:36:42.047 --> 00:36:42.630
it worked out.

00:36:42.630 --> 00:36:45.383
So this is a response of
the right TPJ to the belief

00:36:45.383 --> 00:36:47.550
and photo condition, just
like I showed you before--

00:36:47.550 --> 00:36:50.320
higher when you do the belief
task than the photo task.

00:36:50.320 --> 00:36:52.380
OK, just a reality check--

00:36:52.380 --> 00:36:54.540
key question, what
is the response

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:57.030
of the right TPJ in that main
experiment with the three

00:36:57.030 --> 00:37:00.720
conditions we just described?

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:02.910
And here's what it does.

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:05.550
It's high only in the
thought condition,

00:37:05.550 --> 00:37:08.760
only when you're reading about,
thinking about another person's

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:10.770
thoughts.

00:37:10.770 --> 00:37:12.780
And that's significantly
higher than

00:37:12.780 --> 00:37:19.530
either the external properties
or the visceral states.

00:37:19.530 --> 00:37:21.150
And those two, even
though it looks

00:37:21.150 --> 00:37:22.380
like there's a
little bit of a trend

00:37:22.380 --> 00:37:24.000
that visceral is
higher than external,

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:25.110
that's not significant.

00:37:25.800 --> 00:37:27.180
Yeah?

00:37:27.180 --> 00:37:29.190
AUDIENCE: On the
previous slide, is it,

00:37:29.190 --> 00:37:30.950
like, thoughts and/or desires?

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.170
So like, why can't--

00:37:35.170 --> 00:37:37.380
like, I was just confused
about the example

00:37:37.380 --> 00:37:40.290
for the visceral case, if
your smelling food everywhere.

00:37:40.290 --> 00:37:42.088
Like, couldn't that
fall under it--

00:37:42.088 --> 00:37:43.630
NANCY KANWISHER:
That's a good point.

00:37:43.630 --> 00:37:44.580
Yes, it could.

00:37:44.580 --> 00:37:47.830
Yes, you could infer a desire
in that case, absolutely.

00:37:47.830 --> 00:37:49.650
Yeah, that's right.

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:51.900
So yeah, that's a good point.

00:37:51.900 --> 00:37:56.972
It's intended to just identify
the vivid, visceral state.

00:37:56.972 --> 00:37:58.680
And it's probably hard
to do that with it

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:02.160
without invoking some
kind of desires here.

00:38:02.160 --> 00:38:05.130
Yeah, I would consider
it a confound for that,

00:38:05.130 --> 00:38:07.480
for that particular example.

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:09.370
I'm guessing it was
not so for the others.

00:38:09.370 --> 00:38:12.720
In fact, it sort of
couldn't have been,

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:15.780
given the way this
came out, right?

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:16.590
But good point.

00:38:18.010 --> 00:38:19.240
OK, so--

00:38:22.090 --> 00:38:25.720
OK, so-- and if you
do a whole group

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:27.790
analysis, the whole
brain, and you

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:30.880
say what bits do you get
in a contrast of reasoning

00:38:30.880 --> 00:38:33.790
about another person's
thoughts versus their external

00:38:33.790 --> 00:38:36.850
appearance, or their
visceral states,

00:38:36.850 --> 00:38:38.290
their bodily sensations?

00:38:38.290 --> 00:38:42.280
You get the right TPJ again.

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:44.110
OK, so everybody got this?

00:38:44.110 --> 00:38:48.670
This suggests that the right
TPJ is extremely specifically

00:38:48.670 --> 00:38:50.950
interested in inferring
another person's thoughts,

00:38:50.950 --> 00:38:53.150
not even just their
bodily sensations.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:56.140
So it's not all mental
states of another person

00:38:56.140 --> 00:38:57.208
that engage this region.

00:38:57.208 --> 00:38:58.750
I mean, I find this
quite remarkable,

00:38:58.750 --> 00:39:00.370
because that's so specific.

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:03.040
Before you hear about
this, you think, OK,

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:05.742
thinking about another person's
thirst or hunger or pain,

00:39:05.742 --> 00:39:08.200
is that really different than
thinking about their beliefs?

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:09.890
But oh yes, it's different.

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:10.390
Right?

00:39:10.390 --> 00:39:13.220
The TPJ does believe it's not
thirst and hunger and pain.

00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:13.720
Yes?

00:39:13.720 --> 00:39:17.055
AUDIENCE: What about
your own thoughts and--

00:39:17.055 --> 00:39:18.430
NANCY KANWISHER:
Yeah, so there's

00:39:18.430 --> 00:39:19.970
a whole literature on this.

00:39:19.970 --> 00:39:24.040
And I think if you--

00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:26.920
OK, so first of all, we need
to get the levels straight.

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:28.813
When you're just
thinking, you're

00:39:28.813 --> 00:39:29.980
not thinking about thinking.

00:39:29.980 --> 00:39:31.730
You're just thinking,
right, so you're not

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:33.460
engaging this region.

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:35.668
So when we're talking
about thoughts,

00:39:35.668 --> 00:39:37.960
we're talking about you
thinking about another person's

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:38.870
thoughts.

00:39:38.870 --> 00:39:40.780
So the parallel
would be thinking

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:42.970
about your own thoughts, right.

00:39:42.970 --> 00:39:44.350
So I think--

00:39:44.350 --> 00:39:47.722
I can't tell you exactly what
the literature is on this,

00:39:47.722 --> 00:39:49.180
I'm sure there's
a few experiments.

00:39:49.180 --> 00:39:50.555
But I think what
you'd have to do

00:39:50.555 --> 00:39:54.190
is adopt that kind
of meta perspective

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:56.500
on yourself, right--

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:59.260
a lot of our thinking
is sort of thinking

00:39:59.260 --> 00:40:03.105
about thinking, but not in a
very explicit, separable way.

00:40:03.105 --> 00:40:04.480
I'm not being very
clear on this,

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:11.830
but I think if you ask
people for example,

00:40:11.830 --> 00:40:14.110
when you saw this surprising
event, whatever it is--

00:40:14.110 --> 00:40:15.520
you make something up--

00:40:15.520 --> 00:40:18.400
what were you thinking?

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:20.478
You might engage that region.

00:40:20.478 --> 00:40:23.020
I realize I'm not totally sure
if there's literature on this.

00:40:23.020 --> 00:40:23.680
Heather, is there?

00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:25.055
There must be
literature on this.

00:40:25.055 --> 00:40:30.120
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:30.946
Yeah.

00:40:30.946 --> 00:40:37.925
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:37.925 --> 00:40:40.130
You get MPFC for that, yeah.

00:40:40.130 --> 00:40:41.170
Or go ahead--

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:51.120
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:53.680
AUDIENCE: --and very, it's
kind of, like, intricate--

00:40:53.680 --> 00:40:59.220
[INAUDIBLE] --it will
two networks that are--

00:40:59.220 --> 00:41:02.490
NANCY KANWISHER: But not just
rTPJ, right, rTPJ and other

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:03.450
regions.

00:41:03.450 --> 00:41:07.440
Yeah, so you could get
some rTPJ when answering

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:09.060
those kinds of questions.

00:41:09.060 --> 00:41:11.810
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:11.810 --> 00:41:12.926
NANCY KANWISHER: Uh-huh.

00:41:12.926 --> 00:41:15.140
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:17.720
NANCY KANWISHER: OK, so you
get something in the vicinity.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:20.030
I'm just trying to get--

00:41:20.030 --> 00:41:23.560
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:25.480
Right, but the
other part of this

00:41:25.480 --> 00:41:27.970
is, I bet you have to do
something quite explicit

00:41:27.970 --> 00:41:29.720
to do that, because
in some sense,

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:31.990
we're thinking about
our own thoughts

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:33.790
kind of implicitly
a lot of the time.

00:41:33.790 --> 00:41:36.040
Right, so I'm guessing
that it's when

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:38.320
you ask about it explicitly.

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:40.650
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
forget the details of--

00:41:40.650 --> 00:41:42.192
[INAUDIBLE]

00:41:42.192 --> 00:41:43.150
NANCY KANWISHER: Right.

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:44.726
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:44.726 --> 00:41:45.684
NANCY KANWISHER: Right.

00:41:45.684 --> 00:41:47.040
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:47.998
NANCY KANWISHER: Right.

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:52.430
OK, anyway, good question.

00:41:52.430 --> 00:41:54.680
I'm sorry, I don't have a
totally adequate answer yet.

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:56.347
I'm guessing the
literature doesn't have

00:41:56.347 --> 00:41:58.820
a totally adequate answer yet.

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:05.700
OK, all right, so
recall that I mentioned

00:42:05.700 --> 00:42:09.210
that the contrast between
doing the false belief

00:42:09.210 --> 00:42:13.140
task versus the false photo
task gets not just the rTPJ,

00:42:13.140 --> 00:42:15.750
it also gets this
medial frontal region.

00:42:15.750 --> 00:42:17.640
OK, and that medial
frontal region

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:21.060
responds more to the belief
than photograph task, like this.

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:25.440
What does it do in this
split between thoughts,

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:27.670
visceral thinking about
other people's thoughts,

00:42:27.670 --> 00:42:31.950
their visceral states, and
their external appearance?

00:42:31.950 --> 00:42:34.600
It doesn't care.

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:38.710
OK, so there's a real division
between these different brain

00:42:38.710 --> 00:42:41.680
regions that are engaged when
you do the false belief task.

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:45.280
The rTPJ is very
specifically interested in--

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:46.720
very specifically
engaged when you

00:42:46.720 --> 00:42:48.370
think about another
person's thoughts,

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:51.040
not when you think about
their bodily sensations.

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:54.280
The medial prefrontal region
is engaged in all three

00:42:54.280 --> 00:42:56.290
of these conditions.

00:42:56.290 --> 00:43:01.510
OK, so what it looks like
is that of these three

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:05.500
hypotheses, any time you
think about another person,

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:06.905
that's true of the MPFC.

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:14.170
Whereas the right TPJ
responds specifically

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:18.410
when you attribute thoughts
and desires to another person.

00:43:18.410 --> 00:43:18.910
OK?

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:24.960
OK, now you may have been
wondering about the fact

00:43:24.960 --> 00:43:27.300
that all of these
experiments are using words.

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:29.700
It's kind of not, like,
normal social cognition.

00:43:29.700 --> 00:43:32.950
You're reading about
all this stuff.

00:43:32.950 --> 00:43:35.940
And if these regions
were really doing

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:37.397
what we're claiming
they're doing,

00:43:37.397 --> 00:43:39.480
we should be able to find
them in other situations

00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:44.170
where you make inferences
about other agents' beliefs.

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:48.090
So in more recent
experiments, they've

00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:50.790
been showing Pixar movies
to subjects in the scanner.

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:54.750
So you can just watch
yourself make a few inferences

00:43:54.750 --> 00:43:56.070
about the agent's beliefs.

00:43:56.070 --> 00:43:58.920
Imagine you're watching
this in the scanner,

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:02.130
and just let's just do a little
bit of it to get the gist.

00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:03.070
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:44:03.070 --> 00:44:08.250
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:44:08.250 --> 00:44:09.345
No words, it's a key.

00:44:15.300 --> 00:44:18.900
OK, so there's a whole little
microcosm of mental states

00:44:18.900 --> 00:44:19.860
here.

00:44:19.860 --> 00:44:23.830
In other parts of this same
six minute Pixar movie,

00:44:23.830 --> 00:44:26.320
there's very vivid
bodily sensations.

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:29.040
There's a porcupine
who inflicts real pain

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:32.280
with porcupine quills,
so there's bodily states,

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:35.520
and inferences
about bodily states,

00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:39.090
and inferences about
mental states that go on.

00:44:39.090 --> 00:44:42.870
And by showing this movie
to subjects in the scanner,

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:46.620
and then labeling which parts
of the movie require the viewer

00:44:46.620 --> 00:44:48.840
to make inferences about
the thoughts and beliefs

00:44:48.840 --> 00:44:52.560
of the protagonists, and which
require them to make inferences

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:56.280
about bodily sensations--
like, usually pain--

00:44:56.280 --> 00:45:00.390
if you do that contrast,
you find the same set

00:45:00.390 --> 00:45:05.430
of regions, the rTPJ and
its left hemisphere bit,

00:45:05.430 --> 00:45:07.500
and you find some
medial prefrontal stuff,

00:45:07.500 --> 00:45:09.750
and you find some other stuff.

00:45:09.750 --> 00:45:11.410
OK, so what does that mean?

00:45:11.410 --> 00:45:14.730
That means that you don't need
words to identify this region.

00:45:14.730 --> 00:45:17.490
If you induce the same
cognitive processes just

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:20.940
from watching a
wordless movie, you

00:45:20.940 --> 00:45:24.420
show the same
selective activations.

00:45:24.420 --> 00:45:26.880
And that's cool,
because it tells us

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:29.970
that this is not about some
kind of verbal reasoning.

00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:32.910
It's really about the kind
of deeper cognitive process,

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:34.500
whether you do it
based on a movie,

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:37.710
or based on a
bunch of sentences.

00:45:37.710 --> 00:45:39.510
And that's a powerful
generalization.

00:45:39.510 --> 00:45:44.610
We like imaging results,
where the result generalizes

00:45:44.610 --> 00:45:46.200
across very different
kinds of tasks.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:48.750
And this really
strengthens the evidence

00:45:48.750 --> 00:45:51.300
that this is really what's
going on in this region.

00:45:51.300 --> 00:45:54.930
And it also means you can
look for this region in kids.

00:45:54.930 --> 00:45:57.660
OK, and I didn't manage to
fit that into this lecture,

00:45:57.660 --> 00:45:59.820
but there's a whole
other research enterprise

00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:03.870
where, in Rebecca's lab,
they've been scanning kids

00:46:03.870 --> 00:46:06.090
watching this Pixar
movie, and asking

00:46:06.090 --> 00:46:08.610
how that region develops.

00:46:08.610 --> 00:46:11.940
And they find that, actually,
the region continues

00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:14.610
to develop even after age four.

00:46:14.610 --> 00:46:15.840
It continues to develop.

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:18.870
And what happens is it
doesn't so much get bigger

00:46:18.870 --> 00:46:20.820
as it gets more selective.

00:46:20.820 --> 00:46:26.700
In the younger kids you
get activation, both for--

00:46:26.700 --> 00:46:28.590
well, it's just less selective.

00:46:28.590 --> 00:46:31.240
Anyway, so this
shows generalization.

00:46:31.240 --> 00:46:35.520
So now we've shown
that we see the rTPJ is

00:46:35.520 --> 00:46:38.250
selective for thinking about
other people's thoughts.

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:40.020
We see that with false photo--

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:42.690
false belief versus
false photo contrast.

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:44.470
We see that it's
highly specific.

00:46:44.470 --> 00:46:47.410
It's not just any thoughts
you have about another person.

00:46:47.410 --> 00:46:49.320
And we see it generalizes
to Pixar movies.

00:46:51.060 --> 00:46:55.800
OK, so let's consider now
moral reasoning as a test

00:46:55.800 --> 00:46:58.890
case for theory of mind.

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:01.530
Why moral reasoning?

00:47:01.530 --> 00:47:03.810
Well, if you think
about it, reasoning

00:47:03.810 --> 00:47:06.750
about what's a morally
acceptable or unacceptable

00:47:06.750 --> 00:47:12.210
action on the part of another
person is all about what

00:47:12.210 --> 00:47:15.780
the person intended
and what they knew.

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:18.270
OK, so intent is
very fundamental.

00:47:18.270 --> 00:47:19.780
It's built into
the legal system.

00:47:19.780 --> 00:47:21.930
Think about the
difference between murder

00:47:21.930 --> 00:47:23.640
and manslaughter.

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:25.740
Right, they both involve
killing another person,

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:28.530
but one is with intent, and
the other is accidental.

00:47:28.530 --> 00:47:32.070
And our common moral
reasoning and our legal system

00:47:32.070 --> 00:47:34.260
cares deeply about
that difference.

00:47:37.770 --> 00:47:40.950
So for example, I'm going to
give you a moral reasoning

00:47:40.950 --> 00:47:43.470
task, and just think about this.

00:47:43.470 --> 00:47:47.280
And your task is going to be to
decide how morally permissible

00:47:47.280 --> 00:47:49.770
is the action described here--

00:47:49.770 --> 00:47:51.360
Grace's action in particular.

00:47:51.360 --> 00:47:53.460
OK, so Grace and her
friend are taking

00:47:53.460 --> 00:47:55.143
a tour of a chemical plant.

00:47:55.143 --> 00:47:57.060
And when Grace goes over
to the coffee machine

00:47:57.060 --> 00:47:59.640
to pour some coffee,
Grace's friend

00:47:59.640 --> 00:48:01.860
asks for some sugar in hers.

00:48:01.860 --> 00:48:05.640
And there's white powder in
a container by the coffee.

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:07.110
The plot thickens.

00:48:07.110 --> 00:48:09.870
The white powder is a very
toxic substance left behind

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:12.390
by a scientist, and
therefore, it's deadly

00:48:12.390 --> 00:48:16.230
when ingested in any form--

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:20.640
versus-- but the container
is labeled sugar,

00:48:20.640 --> 00:48:23.790
so Grace believes that the
white powder by the coffee

00:48:23.790 --> 00:48:26.810
is sugar left by
the kitchen staff.

00:48:26.810 --> 00:48:30.050
So grace puts the substance
in her friend's coffee,

00:48:30.050 --> 00:48:32.870
and her friend drinks
the coffee and dies.

00:48:32.870 --> 00:48:36.470
Now, your question is
how morally permissible

00:48:36.470 --> 00:48:39.620
was Grace's action,
on a scale from one,

00:48:39.620 --> 00:48:44.060
to totally not OK, morally
forbidden, to seven, morally

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:45.140
permissible.

00:48:45.140 --> 00:48:47.810
OK, so think about
that on a scale,

00:48:47.810 --> 00:48:49.860
and write down your number
on a piece of paper.

00:48:49.860 --> 00:48:52.640
You don't have to divulge it.

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:55.130
OK, everybody got the question?

00:48:58.900 --> 00:49:01.570
Everybody decided, more or less?

00:49:01.570 --> 00:49:03.590
OK, write down your number.

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:06.670
Now, consider a slightly
different case--

00:49:06.670 --> 00:49:09.690
slightly, but crucially
different case--

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:12.610
this case is known as
the accidental harm case.

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:16.960
Now consider the
case where instead--

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:22.190
OK, instead of being labeled
sugar, you get the same story,

00:49:22.190 --> 00:49:24.550
but now the container
is labeled toxic.

00:49:24.550 --> 00:49:28.420
So Grace believes that the white
powder is a toxic substance

00:49:28.420 --> 00:49:30.730
left behind by a scientist.

00:49:30.730 --> 00:49:33.340
Nonetheless, she
puts the substance

00:49:33.340 --> 00:49:36.010
in her friend's coffee and
their friend drinks a coffee

00:49:36.010 --> 00:49:36.910
and dies.

00:49:36.910 --> 00:49:39.640
Now, consider how
morally permissible

00:49:39.640 --> 00:49:45.550
is Grace's action, from one,
to totally not OK, to seven,

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:47.560
morally permissible.

00:49:47.560 --> 00:49:48.865
And write down your number.

00:49:53.670 --> 00:49:56.790
OK, how many people gave
a lower number-- that is,

00:49:56.790 --> 00:50:01.110
more morally forbidden for the
second one than the first one.

00:50:01.110 --> 00:50:05.400
OK, if you didn't, you probably
weren't paying attention.

00:50:05.400 --> 00:50:09.090
OK, so you can see
that it's the crux

00:50:09.090 --> 00:50:11.070
of the matter what
Grace believed

00:50:11.070 --> 00:50:12.900
when she did the action.

00:50:12.900 --> 00:50:15.030
OK, that's why we're talking
about moral reasoning

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:17.850
here as a test case
of theory of mind,

00:50:17.850 --> 00:50:20.610
because what the agent knew
at the time of the action

00:50:20.610 --> 00:50:23.340
is of the essence in thinking
about the moral status

00:50:23.340 --> 00:50:24.690
of their action.

00:50:24.690 --> 00:50:26.550
OK, everybody got that--

00:50:26.550 --> 00:50:28.523
OK, so this is a
powerful test case.

00:50:28.523 --> 00:50:30.690
And notice that-- also in
the clip that I showed you

00:50:30.690 --> 00:50:33.660
from Rebecca's Ted
Talk, she showed

00:50:33.660 --> 00:50:39.930
that kids' ability to use an
agent's knowledge in doing what

00:50:39.930 --> 00:50:43.110
you guys just did, that
kicks in a little bit later

00:50:43.110 --> 00:50:45.150
than the standard
false belief task.

00:50:45.150 --> 00:50:49.110
So sometime after they get the
basic idea of false belief,

00:50:49.110 --> 00:50:50.160
they start to apply.

00:50:50.160 --> 00:50:53.880
It takes a while to kick
in in this other case.

00:50:53.880 --> 00:50:58.140
OK, so this is known as
intentional harm as opposed

00:50:58.140 --> 00:51:00.090
to accidental harm.

00:51:00.090 --> 00:51:03.450
OK-- it's just the
terminology in the field.

00:51:03.450 --> 00:51:08.250
OK, so what do you think
will happen in autism?

00:51:08.250 --> 00:51:13.710
If we ask people with
autism these two questions--

00:51:13.710 --> 00:51:16.440
and what do you think
will happen if we

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:19.440
apply TMS to the right TPJ?

00:51:19.440 --> 00:51:22.980
It's right out there on
the lateral surface, just

00:51:22.980 --> 00:51:24.000
asking for it.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.220
So it's a totally
doable experiment.

00:51:26.220 --> 00:51:28.785
It's been done, what
do you think happens?

00:51:30.600 --> 00:51:32.590
OK, let's take the
case with autism.

00:51:32.590 --> 00:51:34.350
How do you think
people with autism

00:51:34.350 --> 00:51:37.970
will respond to
these two questions?

00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:41.350
The same as you guys did?

00:51:41.350 --> 00:51:44.950
Yeah-- yes, Shardoul.

00:51:44.950 --> 00:51:47.890
AUDIENCE: Probably the
average distance between--

00:51:47.890 --> 00:51:50.890
the average distance between how
bad they think the second one

00:51:50.890 --> 00:51:53.650
would be less than
the first one--

00:51:53.650 --> 00:51:54.900
NANCY KANWISHER: Yes, exactly.

00:51:54.900 --> 00:51:55.400
Why?

00:51:58.402 --> 00:51:59.860
AUDIENCE: Because
they might not be

00:51:59.860 --> 00:52:04.000
able to make the
distinction between Grace

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.250
knowing that the
container was toxic

00:52:06.250 --> 00:52:09.610
versus the container
being labeled toxic.

00:52:09.610 --> 00:52:11.830
Like, both then, would
be confounded with just

00:52:11.830 --> 00:52:13.733
like truth and consequence.

00:52:13.733 --> 00:52:15.400
NANCY KANWISHER:
Absolutely, absolutely.

00:52:15.400 --> 00:52:16.400
Did everybody get that--

00:52:16.400 --> 00:52:17.560
share that intuition?

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:21.520
To the extent that autism
is a particular deficit

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:25.570
in understanding what another
person knows or believes,

00:52:25.570 --> 00:52:27.880
that's the only difference
between these two cases.

00:52:27.880 --> 00:52:31.090
To the extent that you have
difficulty representing that,

00:52:31.090 --> 00:52:32.860
you will have less
of a difference

00:52:32.860 --> 00:52:34.900
in your moral judgment
about these two things,

00:52:34.900 --> 00:52:37.450
because you have a hard time
representing that person's

00:52:37.450 --> 00:52:38.350
knowledge.

00:52:38.350 --> 00:52:41.470
It's not that autism is a
deficit in moral reasoning.

00:52:41.470 --> 00:52:44.197
It's that moral
reasoning entails

00:52:44.197 --> 00:52:46.780
thinking about other-- at least
these cases, not all of them--

00:52:46.780 --> 00:52:49.780
but these cases involve thinking
about other people's thoughts

00:52:49.780 --> 00:52:51.250
and taking them into account.

00:52:51.250 --> 00:52:53.260
And to the extent that
that's difficult for you,

00:52:53.260 --> 00:52:55.190
you will make less of a
distinction, exactly--

00:52:55.190 --> 00:52:55.690
right.

00:52:55.690 --> 00:52:57.070
Yeah, was there a
question back there?

00:52:57.070 --> 00:52:57.945
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:57.945 --> 00:53:00.520
NANCY KANWISHER: Yeah, OK.

00:53:00.520 --> 00:53:03.310
OK, what do you
think will happen

00:53:03.310 --> 00:53:07.508
if you zap the rTPJ
with TMS while subjects

00:53:07.508 --> 00:53:08.425
are doing these tasks?

00:53:13.380 --> 00:53:14.095
Yeah?

00:53:14.095 --> 00:53:14.970
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:14.970 --> 00:53:15.603
NANCY KANWISHER: Yeah?

00:53:15.603 --> 00:53:16.728
AUDIENCE: They'd be, like--

00:53:16.728 --> 00:53:18.290
[INAUDIBLE]

00:53:18.290 --> 00:53:19.850
NANCY KANWISHER: Yeah, yeah.

00:53:19.850 --> 00:53:20.990
That's the prediction.

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:24.530
If the rTPJ is the main bit
that's doing the inference

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:27.320
about-- it's representing
the beliefs of others,

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:32.420
then if you zap it, you
might change people's moral

00:53:32.420 --> 00:53:33.470
inferences--

00:53:33.470 --> 00:53:36.280
moral judgments.

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:38.640
That's pretty wild.

00:53:38.640 --> 00:53:40.380
That's what happens.

00:53:40.380 --> 00:53:43.470
Zap the rTPJ, and they
make a smaller distinction

00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:47.910
between accidental harm
and intentional harm.

00:53:47.910 --> 00:53:49.770
OK, so both of those
things are true.

00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:52.890
I won't drag you through all
the details of the experiments.

00:53:52.890 --> 00:53:55.710
But the basic findings from
this whole line of work

00:53:55.710 --> 00:53:59.520
show that, first of
all, neurotypical people

00:53:59.520 --> 00:54:02.910
agree, as you guys did, that
accidental harm is more morally

00:54:02.910 --> 00:54:04.890
permissible than
intentional harm.

00:54:04.890 --> 00:54:10.620
OK, and people with
autism give less

00:54:10.620 --> 00:54:14.370
forgiveness for accidental harm
compared to intentional harm

00:54:14.370 --> 00:54:15.750
than neurotypicals.

00:54:15.750 --> 00:54:19.890
OK-- just because that ability
to represent the key knowledge

00:54:19.890 --> 00:54:22.030
that tells you
it's accidental is

00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:23.280
something they're not good at.

00:54:26.190 --> 00:54:28.050
What is the role of the rTPJ?

00:54:28.050 --> 00:54:31.728
The data show that forgiveness
for accidental harms--

00:54:31.728 --> 00:54:33.270
first of all, I left
this out before,

00:54:33.270 --> 00:54:36.330
is correlated in
neurotypicals with activation

00:54:36.330 --> 00:54:38.530
of the right TPJ
during moral judgment.

00:54:38.530 --> 00:54:40.440
So if you just measure
across a whole bunch

00:54:40.440 --> 00:54:43.350
of those moral judgment
problems how strongly activated

00:54:43.350 --> 00:54:46.740
was your rTPJ as you
read that problem, that's

00:54:46.740 --> 00:54:50.640
correlated with your
ability to forgive somebody

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:52.470
for accidentally
harming someone,

00:54:52.470 --> 00:54:55.920
again showing that there's
a relationship between your

00:54:55.920 --> 00:54:58.950
representing the thoughts
and beliefs of another person

00:54:58.950 --> 00:55:03.540
and your using that information
to exonerate them from harm

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:04.380
they didn't intend.

00:55:04.380 --> 00:55:04.880
Yeah?

00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:08.250
AUDIENCE: For someone with
autism syndrome, are they--

00:55:08.250 --> 00:55:11.760
is it different for thoughts
versus external actions

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:13.920
of the things?

00:55:13.920 --> 00:55:16.630
NANCY KANWISHER:
Yeah, so first of all,

00:55:16.630 --> 00:55:19.320
I'm treating autism
very superficially here.

00:55:19.320 --> 00:55:22.680
It's an extremely
heterogeneous thing

00:55:22.680 --> 00:55:26.160
that varies not just along
a spectrum, you know,

00:55:26.160 --> 00:55:28.800
which it clearly does, but
probably along many spectra,

00:55:28.800 --> 00:55:30.600
and is highly heterogeneous.

00:55:30.600 --> 00:55:36.120
So these experiments are just
done in high functioning adults

00:55:36.120 --> 00:55:37.500
who are--

00:55:37.500 --> 00:55:41.220
totally pass false
belief tasks--

00:55:41.220 --> 00:55:44.220
they pass them later in life,
but they get to-- otherwise,

00:55:44.220 --> 00:55:46.440
you can't test them on
these kinds of experiments.

00:55:46.440 --> 00:55:48.270
And the effects
are quite subtle.

00:55:48.270 --> 00:55:50.850
They're just a slightly
lesser difference

00:55:50.850 --> 00:55:52.555
between accidental
and intentional harm.

00:55:52.555 --> 00:55:54.930
OK, so just to clarify that,
which I probably should have

00:55:54.930 --> 00:55:55.430
said.

00:55:55.430 --> 00:55:58.350
But your question
is, are the deficits

00:55:58.350 --> 00:56:00.552
in autism specific to
thinking about thoughts

00:56:00.552 --> 00:56:02.010
rather than thinking
about actions?

00:56:04.410 --> 00:56:07.380
This is ongoing work,
but a lot of research

00:56:07.380 --> 00:56:11.190
has shown that it is more
specific to thoughts,

00:56:11.190 --> 00:56:13.650
and that a lot of the
stuff you read about just

00:56:13.650 --> 00:56:16.290
basic perceptual difficulties--

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:21.540
I mean, most studies find
that people with autism

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:24.480
are a little bit worse
at face recognition,

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:26.640
but not much worse.

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:30.300
In tasks asking about
goals of actions,

00:56:30.300 --> 00:56:33.510
like reaching for objects--
what is that person's intention?

00:56:33.510 --> 00:56:36.220
Mostly, they don't find
a deficit in autism.

00:56:36.220 --> 00:56:39.780
So the perceptual--
basic seeing people

00:56:39.780 --> 00:56:44.100
and seeing what they're
doing is much less impaired.

00:56:44.100 --> 00:56:46.110
That's what the current
literature suggests.

00:56:46.110 --> 00:56:47.880
There's always the
worry that we're not

00:56:47.880 --> 00:56:51.390
asking in the right way, or
testing in the right way.

00:56:51.390 --> 00:56:54.840
And the literature is highly
inconsistent from one study

00:56:54.840 --> 00:56:55.410
to the next.

00:56:55.410 --> 00:56:58.890
I used to work on autism and I
just couldn't stand it anymore,

00:56:58.890 --> 00:57:00.540
because every time
a study's done,

00:57:00.540 --> 00:57:02.430
it gets the opposite
of the previous study.

00:57:02.430 --> 00:57:04.800
I think as a population--
so heterogeneous.

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:06.930
But from a gloss, it
looks like there's

00:57:06.930 --> 00:57:09.340
more of a deficit in the
inferences about thoughts

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:10.590
than inferences about actions.

00:57:10.590 --> 00:57:10.890
Yeah?

00:57:10.890 --> 00:57:12.360
AUDIENCE: I just
want to clarify.

00:57:12.360 --> 00:57:15.180
So the autistic subjects
are also explicitly told

00:57:15.180 --> 00:57:17.082
that Grace believes--

00:57:17.082 --> 00:57:17.790
blah, blah, blah.

00:57:17.790 --> 00:57:18.420
Yes?

00:57:18.420 --> 00:57:19.920
It's explicit--

00:57:19.920 --> 00:57:24.525
NANCY KANWISHER: No, it's
exactly what I gave here.

00:57:24.525 --> 00:57:26.400
Yeah, no Grace believes--
yeah, you're right.

00:57:26.400 --> 00:57:27.330
Grace believes.

00:57:27.330 --> 00:57:27.960
Yes--

00:57:27.960 --> 00:57:30.870
AUDIENCE: Explicitly being--
and in spite of that, it's--

00:57:30.870 --> 00:57:31.920
[INAUDIBLE]

00:57:31.920 --> 00:57:34.710
NANCY KANWISHER:
Yep, yeah, yeah.

00:57:34.710 --> 00:57:36.960
And so I think you can think
of this as a subtle case.

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:40.830
These are people who pass the
explicit false belief task.

00:57:40.830 --> 00:57:42.690
But like the 7-year-old
kids, there's

00:57:42.690 --> 00:57:45.405
one thing if you're asked--
what does this person believe,

00:57:45.405 --> 00:57:47.280
and another if you're
asked a moral reasoning

00:57:47.280 --> 00:57:49.830
task for which you have
to realize to bring

00:57:49.830 --> 00:57:50.940
the belief into account.

00:57:50.940 --> 00:57:54.615
It takes more of your
own kind of active--

00:57:54.615 --> 00:57:55.740
was there another question?

00:57:55.740 --> 00:57:57.000
AUDIENCE: What if you ask--

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.250
like, instead of Grace,
what if you say it's you?

00:57:59.250 --> 00:58:00.500
NANCY KANWISHER: What if what?

00:58:00.500 --> 00:58:03.293
AUDIENCE: You ask
them about themselves.

00:58:03.293 --> 00:58:04.710
So you and your
friends are taking

00:58:04.710 --> 00:58:06.543
a tour of the chemical
plants, and give them

00:58:06.543 --> 00:58:07.590
the exact same scenario.

00:58:07.590 --> 00:58:08.971
Would that be any different?

00:58:10.250 --> 00:58:12.000
NANCY KANWISHER: Yeah,
that's interesting.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:15.380
It's like the question
about to what--

00:58:15.380 --> 00:58:15.880
sorry--

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:17.340
AUDIENCE: What was the question?

00:58:17.340 --> 00:58:18.810
NANCY KANWISHER: Question
is, suppose you ask people

00:58:18.810 --> 00:58:21.120
with autism this same question,
but it's not about Grace.

00:58:21.120 --> 00:58:21.750
It's about you.

00:58:21.750 --> 00:58:22.725
You do all of this.

00:58:24.880 --> 00:58:25.690
I'm not sure.

00:58:25.690 --> 00:58:26.287
Good question.

00:58:26.287 --> 00:58:27.870
Probably, somebody
has looked at that.

00:58:27.870 --> 00:58:28.370
Yeah.

00:58:28.370 --> 00:58:31.590
AUDIENCE: I'm not sure if
you answered already, but do

00:58:31.590 --> 00:58:33.420
people with autism
have something

00:58:33.420 --> 00:58:34.968
different in their rTPJ?

00:58:34.968 --> 00:58:36.510
NANCY KANWISHER:
We're getting there.

00:58:36.510 --> 00:58:38.550
You should absolutely
be wondering that,

00:58:38.550 --> 00:58:39.360
and I haven't yet.

00:58:39.360 --> 00:58:40.660
And we're getting there.

00:58:40.660 --> 00:58:41.490
Good that you ask.

00:58:41.490 --> 00:58:43.323
In fact, that's probably
my very next slide.

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:48.270
OK, so causal role--

00:58:48.270 --> 00:58:51.900
we showed the causal role of the
rTPJ in neurotypical subjects,

00:58:51.900 --> 00:58:56.280
you zap the rTPJ and you
slightly reduce the difference

00:58:56.280 --> 00:59:00.210
in moral permissibility
of the accidental harms

00:59:00.210 --> 00:59:01.890
and the intentional harms.

00:59:01.890 --> 00:59:04.320
OK, so all of these
findings suggest

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:06.510
that the rTPJ is
causally engaged

00:59:06.510 --> 00:59:08.970
in understanding the difference
between intentional and

00:59:08.970 --> 00:59:13.020
accidental actions, and
that ability is specifically

00:59:13.020 --> 00:59:15.510
disrupted and autism, All.

00:59:15.510 --> 00:59:17.940
Of which leads to the
natural prediction

00:59:17.940 --> 00:59:21.600
that Gisella just made
about the rTPJ in autism.

00:59:22.630 --> 00:59:23.610
So what do you think?

00:59:23.610 --> 00:59:25.985
Is the rTPJ affected in autism?

00:59:25.985 --> 00:59:27.360
How many-- raise
your hand if you

00:59:27.360 --> 00:59:28.818
think there's going
to be something

00:59:28.818 --> 00:59:34.120
different in the rTPJ autism
versus typical subjects.

00:59:34.120 --> 00:59:37.870
OK, raise your hand if
you think there isn't.

00:59:37.870 --> 00:59:40.570
Not sure-- OK, well,
you're sort of both right

00:59:40.570 --> 00:59:41.500
in different ways.

00:59:41.500 --> 00:59:49.090
OK, so the answer is this--
so in Rebecca Saxe's lab,

00:59:49.090 --> 00:59:52.120
they did a study with
a really large number

00:59:52.120 --> 00:59:53.120
of typical subjects.

00:59:53.120 --> 00:59:57.130
It's-- because of this
heterogeneity in the autism

00:59:57.130 --> 00:59:59.740
population, it's really hard
to get a stable result you can

00:59:59.740 --> 01:00:00.970
believe.

01:00:00.970 --> 01:00:02.660
And it helps to have
a really large--

01:00:02.660 --> 01:00:04.600
it's hard to get
enough autism subjects,

01:00:04.600 --> 01:00:06.250
so we try and we get
as many as we can.

01:00:06.250 --> 01:00:08.250
And the most you ever get
in a study around here

01:00:08.250 --> 01:00:11.530
is 20, 30, and that's
a big struggle.

01:00:11.530 --> 01:00:14.560
But it helps to have a really
large neurotypical control

01:00:14.560 --> 01:00:16.510
population to reduce
your error bars

01:00:16.510 --> 01:00:19.060
on what the neurotypical
population shows.

01:00:19.060 --> 01:00:21.610
So this study is probably
the biggest that's been done.

01:00:21.610 --> 01:00:26.650
They had 31 high functioning
people with autism and 462

01:00:26.650 --> 01:00:28.720
neurotypical individuals.

01:00:28.720 --> 01:00:31.630
They didn't just go run
400 new subjects for this.

01:00:31.630 --> 01:00:33.700
When you run that
localizer task,

01:00:33.700 --> 01:00:35.330
you've got it in
every study you run.

01:00:35.330 --> 01:00:38.110
And so then you can take all
those localizer tasks across

01:00:38.110 --> 01:00:40.330
hundreds of subjects-- so--

01:00:40.330 --> 01:00:44.200
and so what they find is,
both if you look at regions

01:00:44.200 --> 01:00:46.930
of interest analysis,
like find rTPJ,

01:00:46.930 --> 01:00:50.360
and if you do a whole
brain group analysis,

01:00:50.360 --> 01:00:55.078
you find no differences
between people with autism--

01:00:55.078 --> 01:00:56.620
high functioning
people with autism--

01:00:56.620 --> 01:01:00.400
and typical subjects in the
size, location, or response

01:01:00.400 --> 01:01:02.195
magnitude of the rTPJ.

01:01:06.790 --> 01:01:10.990
OK-- when people do
theory of mind tasks.

01:01:10.990 --> 01:01:12.790
So you should be surprised.

01:01:12.790 --> 01:01:13.930
Everyone is surprised.

01:01:13.930 --> 01:01:15.340
You all made the prediction.

01:01:15.340 --> 01:01:18.280
Everyone else made
the prediction too.

01:01:18.280 --> 01:01:19.405
And that's pretty bizarre.

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:28.120
But does that mean that the
rTPJ is not affected in ASD?

01:01:32.240 --> 01:01:33.240
Shardoul?

01:01:33.240 --> 01:01:37.160
AUDIENCE: If we feed it-- the
information from the rTPJ is

01:01:37.160 --> 01:01:39.913
not used by other
parts of the brain to--

01:01:39.913 --> 01:01:40.740
[INAUDIBLE]

01:01:40.740 --> 01:01:42.532
NANCY KANWISHER: That's
a great hypothesis.

01:01:42.532 --> 01:01:44.210
Maybe the information
is in there,

01:01:44.210 --> 01:01:46.100
and it's some kind of
a disconnection thing,

01:01:46.100 --> 01:01:50.210
and so it can't be accessed
by other processes.

01:01:50.210 --> 01:01:51.440
Right, absolutely.

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:52.700
What's another hypothesis?

01:01:55.220 --> 01:01:56.210
Yeah, Isabelle?

01:01:56.210 --> 01:01:57.727
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:57.727 --> 01:01:58.685
NANCY KANWISHER: Sorry?

01:01:58.685 --> 01:02:00.970
AUDIENCE: It's being processed
in a different order?

01:02:00.970 --> 01:02:01.840
NANCY KANWISHER: In
a different order.

01:02:01.840 --> 01:02:02.829
What do you mean?

01:02:02.829 --> 01:02:06.930
