01:15:02.550 --> 01:15:03.980
I can just ask.

01:15:03.980 --> 01:15:05.570
All right-- anyway,
does everybody

01:15:05.570 --> 01:15:07.080
get this basic idea here?

01:15:07.080 --> 01:15:10.250
So the thing-- the rTPJ is
there in the high functioning

01:15:10.250 --> 01:15:11.690
people with autism,
but it doesn't

01:15:11.690 --> 01:15:13.400
hold the same information.

01:15:13.400 --> 01:15:15.370
OK-- all right.

01:15:16.982 --> 01:15:18.940
All right, so where do
we get with all of this?

01:15:18.940 --> 01:15:21.550
We used all of this
stuff on moral reasoning

01:15:21.550 --> 01:15:25.150
as a way to look at the
rTPJ and theory of mind.

01:15:25.150 --> 01:15:29.830
We found that people
with ASD put less weight

01:15:29.830 --> 01:15:31.660
on a person's
beliefs when judging

01:15:31.660 --> 01:15:35.860
the moral permissibility
of an action.

01:15:35.860 --> 01:15:39.220
TMS to the rTPJ
disrupts moral judgment.

01:15:39.220 --> 01:15:42.220
Pattern analysis shows
that the TPJ distinguishes

01:15:42.220 --> 01:15:44.170
between intentional
and accidental harm

01:15:44.170 --> 01:15:47.260
in neurotypicals, but
not in people with ASD.

01:15:47.260 --> 01:15:49.390
OK, so there's a nice little
story developing here.

01:15:49.390 --> 01:15:52.380
I'm sure it's not
the whole deal.